issue.body:
Description

Shifting a signed 32-bit integer representing the number 1, to the left by 31 bits is undefined. This is a bug. However It does not appear to impact security.

src/arith_uint256.cpp: base_uint<BITS>::bits()​: Line 177
```
for (int bits = 31; bits > 0; bits--) {
    if (pn[pos] & 1 << bits)
    return 32 * pos + bits + 1;
}
```
``pn[]`` is ``uint32_t``. ``bits`` is an integer (loop variable). ``1 << bits`` is a signed number (i.e. ``1``) shifted by 31 bits, which is undefined behaviour, because ``1 << 31`` = 2​<sup>31</sup>. ​However, a signed 32-bit number can only represent a number in the range -2<sup>31</sup>​ to 2<sup>​31</sup>​ - 1.

Remediation

Suggest the following code:
```
for (​size_t​ bits = 31; bits > 0; bits--) {   
    if (pn[pos] & ​1U​ << bits)
    return 32 * pos + bits + 1;
}
```

